[Deal "E:74.AQ862.Q6.A843 KQJT.T9.743.KT72 8653.K54.KJT85.Q A92.J73.A92.J965"]
[Declarer "E"]
[Contract "4H"]
[Result ""]
[Auction "E"]
1H pass 3H pass 4H pass pass pass
[BCFlags "1f"]
[RotationNote "Board 3, chOption: E, chBasis: S, basisKind:Declarer, nOption:1, nBasis: 2, nRot: 3, useStandardVul: true"]
[BoardVersionToken "1968fd36c8b086f9099399c76b702d0026e747fdd27ab9676255387de35192db"]
[Category "Declarer Play"]
[Difficulty "intermediate"]
[SkillPath "declarer_play/suit_establishment"]
[Student "S"]
{Some pretty agressive bidding gets you to a challenging game. East is to play 4\H. South leads the \SK, overtaken by North's \SA. North returns a \S to South's \ST, and he then plays the \SQ.

Losers:   \S=2  \H=0  \D=1  \C=3  Total = 6

With 2 tricks already gone you still have 4 losers. You could consider ruffing the 3 \C losers in dummy but that would just create a trump loser even when trumps are splitting 3-2. So it looks like you will have to establish the \D suit for discards. You could pull trumps and then play your \DQ, hoping the defenders will grab their \DA immediately. But unless they are real novices they will hold it up one round and you'll no longer be able to reach dummy.

The solution is to establish the \Ds before you use up dummy's \HK.

Ruff the third \S, then play \DQ, (which they will duck), and another \D, (which they will probably take). Win whatever they return, pull trumps ending in dummy, and enjoy your 3 \D winners.

If North does not take the second \D you continue the suit, and whether you ruff or discard a loser you still make the contract.}
[Play "W"]SK

